  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Level Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalizing financial transactions intended to conceal illegal proceeds\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishing reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Imposing significant penalties and potential criminal charges\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\n4. Penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Civil and criminal prosecution\n\n5. State Level:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\nThese statutes are designed to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes involving the disguising of illegally obtained money as legitimate income.",
